{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_016ix4QJFA8EFi3YjLQvFsCm","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The available images are:\n- `rabbitmq:3.9-management` (already running)\n- `rabbitmq:3.12-management`\n- `rabbitmq:4.1-management`\n\nWait, but the kind node shows `rabbitmq:3.12-management` and `rabbitmq:3.9-management` in crictl. The docker images show also `rabbitmq:4.1-management` and `rabbitmq:3.12-management`.\n\nBut going 3.9 → 3.12 → 4.1 skips versions (hence \"skip_upgrade\"). This is the \"manual_skip_upgrade\" case - the upgrade path skips intermediate versions.\nLooking at what's actually pre-pulled on the kind node, only 3.12 and 4.1 are available, so the upgrade chain would be 3.9 → 3.12 → 4.1, which skips 3.10, 3.11, 3.13, and 4.0. According to RabbitMQ's documentation, rolling upgrades only work between consecutive minor versions, so skipping versions requires a different approach.\n\nThe test is labeled \"manual_skip_upgrade,\" which suggests the agent needs to recognize that a direct rolling upgrade won't work and handle it differently. I should check the oracle and test.yaml to understand what's actually expected, and also verify whether the 4.1-management image needs to be loaded into the kind cluster.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2221,"cache_read_input_tokens":34107,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2221},"output_tokens":44,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ec4bed2d-f2eb-45a6-8f17-10f0087f0ba3","uuid":"38669af9-a0eb-4e96-815e-b465d5fda979","request_id":"req_011CcRLdJDrwoN2PisdZMtFV"}
