{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01DerZfmUSnC9hPosMYZn3UK","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I've saved the message content: msg-1, msg-2, msg-3, msg-4, msg-5 - all 5 messages. They were retrieved with `requeue: true` so they're still in the queue.\n\nNow I have:\n1. Queue definition: `app-queue`, durable, classic type\n2. Messages: msg-1 through msg-5\n3. Vhost: /app\n\nNow I need to:\n1. Scale down to 0\n2. Wipe the Mnesia data on all 3 PVCs  \n3. Patch the image to 4.1\n4. Scale back up to 3\n5. Recreate the /app vhost and app-queue\n6. Republish the 5 messages\n7. Verify everything works\n\nFor wiping the Mnesia data, I'll need to spin up temporary pods that mount each PVC and delete the `/var/lib/rabbitmq/mnesia/` directory, which holds the cluster state and queue metadata. This gives us a fresh cluster on startup. Let me work through the execution, though I'm realizing there's something important to consider about what happens when I wipe the Mnesia directory and restart.\n\nWith the peer discovery configured via the Kubernetes ConfigMap using the k8s peer discovery plugin, the three nodes should be able to form a cluster even with a fresh start. When all nodes start clean, the first node (rabbitmq-0) initializes fresh, then rabbitmq-1 and rabbitmq-2 discover and join it through the Kubernetes API. The existing ConfigMap setup should handle this correctly.\n\nI'll proceed with the wipe using temporary busybox pods mounted to each PVC to delete the Mnesia tables, but I need to be careful about what exactly I'm removing.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":493,"cache_read_input_tokens":65440,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":493},"output_tokens":31,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":