{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01ECoj6azgPvpvA7PGBD9RnL","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The wipe succeeded. For wipe-0, it seems the `/mnt/rabbitmq` directory was deleted (so `ls /mnt` shows nothing). For wipe-1 and wipe-2, `ls /mnt` shows `mnesia` meaning the Mnesia directory still exists. Let me verify...\n\nWait, looking at the command: `rm -rf /mnt/rabbitmq`. The data is mounted at `/mnt`, so I'm trying to delete `/mnt/rabbitmq` directory. But the actual data is in `/var/lib/rabbitmq/` in the pod. When we mount the PVC at `/mnt`, the data inside the PVC would be the contents of `/var/lib/rabbitmq/` (from when RabbitMQ was running).\nActually, the PVC is mounted at `/var/lib/rabbitmq` in the StatefulSet, so when I mount it at `/mnt` for inspection, the contents would be directly in `/mnt` — things like `mnesia`, `.erlang.cookie`, `.rabbitmq` — not in a subdirectory. That means `rm -rf /mnt/rabbitmq` wouldn't find anything to delete since there's no `rabbitmq` subdirectory there.\n\nThe right approach would be to clear everything with `rm -rf /mnt/*` or target specific directories like `rm -rf /mnt/mnesia`. Let me check what's actually stored on these PVCs now.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":668,"cache_read_input_tokens":66993,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":668},"output_tokens":22,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ec4bed2d-f2eb-45a6-8f17-10f0087f0ba3","uuid":"dfa38b86-867e-4bcc-9e61-b213a3099504","request_id":"req_011CcRMngZtkthPPnaLzy9SR"}
